        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Band 7

We propose to map the primary ALMA beam in Orion South centred at RA= 05h35m13.550s, Dec = 05º23'59.14'' (J2000) which is the position of the potential exciting source. A spatial resolution of 0.4" is required to resolve the exciting source which is &lt; 0.6" in size at 1.2mm. Fig 2 shows that the hot core source size is likely &lt; 5" (I.e. In between the co outflow lobes) and therefore is contained in the primary beam.  Therefore mosaicing is not required, nor do we need the ACA to recover the short spacings.

Previous  HIFI observations of SO2, HCO+, CS, &amp; CH3OH toward Orion S shows the line widths are typically 4 - 6 km/s (with most nearer to 4 km/s). Therefore 0.2 km/s resolution is necessary to fully spectrally resolve the line profiles.
The peak continuum flux density at 1.3 mm (Zapata et al. 2005) scaled to the ALMA synthesized beam of 0.4" and a wavelength of 850 microns (using beta = 1.3 and T = 80 K ; Zapata et al. 2005) yields 51 mJY/beam. Thus, with a sensitivity of 1.5 mJy/ we will be able to easily detect the continuum emission.

The SO2 &amp; CH3OH peak fluxes are expected to be &gt; 5 mJy/Beam (McMullen 1993 scaled to ALMA beam). Therefore we can expect to achieve a minimum S/N of 3. The CS 7-6 line flux is expected to be relatively stronger (~10 mJy/beam from HIFI observations assuming emission fills the HIFI beam and then scaled to ALMA beam of 0.4").  There are no previous observations of CH3CN in Orion South but if it is similar to what that seen in the HMSF region G35.20–0.74 N Sánchez-Monge et al. (2013) we expect CH3CN lines that are ~ 10-200 mJY/beam in strength. This should provide a minimum S/N of 7. We used the peak flux of the weakest line (~ 5 mJy/beam) in the Field setup.

The data rates of 15.13 MB/s slightly exceed the policy of 12 MB/s. However we believe this is justified by the fact that we need multiple lines of CH3OH, CH3CN and SO2 in order to properly analyse the emission using rotation diagrams and LTE and non-LTE models. Multiple transitions, spanning a range of energy (see Table 1) are required to fully sample parameter space. In addition, we have used spectrometer setups that provide the required spectral resolution (~ 0.2 km/s) and also leave sufficient baseline frequency to subtract the continuum from the spectral line emission. Also note, that in some cases, we take advantage of larger bandwidth to obtain simultaneous observations of more than one spectral line. For example, for the CH3CN using a baseband-4 setup "Full" plus the 1/4 baseband observation in baseband-3 allows us to obtain 9 k-ladder transitions of the 18-17 line.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
