    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Orion South is the nearest start forming region associated with a hot core.  It also contains a number of powerful, highly- collimated outflows seen in interferometric and single dish maps. The central massive protostar produces ionizing radiation which heats the circumstellar dust, and the associated outflow can produce shocks, both of which can enhance the chemistry in the hot core environment.  Despite the fact that Orion South is the closest hot core (Orion KL being in dispute as a hot core), very little is known about the physical conditions in the local environment.
We propose to study the physical conditions (temperature, column density, etc.) of the nearest hot core using CS 7-6, HCO+ 3-2, and a variety of CH3OH, CH3CN, and SO2 transitions (spanning an energy range of Eup ~ 30 - 500 K).  These observations, combined with a combination of rotation diagram analyses and spectral line profile modelling, will be used to probe the physical conditions in both the hot core and the shock excited gas close to the protostar.</prp:abstract>
